    title: "Epiglottitis",
    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Epiglottitis", content: "Epiglottitis is a rapidly progressive, life-threatening infection of the epiglottis and surrounding supraglottic structures, historically caused by Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib) in children but now more common in adults due to Hib vaccination — current causative organisms include Streptococcus species, Staphylococcus aureus, and non-typeable H. influenzae. Infection causes cellulitis and edema of the epiglottis and aryepiglottic folds, which can rapidly progress to complete upper airway obstruction. The classic presentation in children includes abrupt onset of high fever, severe sore throat, dysphagia, drooling, muffled voice, and the 'tripod' or 'sniffing' position (sitting upright, leaning forward with neck hyperextended to maximize airway patency). Emergency management prioritizes airway control — the patient should never be laid supine or examined with a tongue blade (may precipitate laryngospasm and complete obstruction), with controlled intubation in the operating room by the most experienced available provider, followed by IV antibiotics (third-generation cephalosporin) and corticosteroids." },
